===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|ls=ic|ls2=psc|丰|土|寸|c1=p|c2=s|c3=s|t1=seedling|t2=earth|t3=hand|abb1=yes}} – mark boundaries by planting trees. Compare {{zh-m|*邦}}.

Originally {{zh-m|*丰}}, depicting a tree seedling. Variants that added any combination of {{zh-m|*土|earth}}, {{zh-m|*又|hand}}, {{zh-m|*田|field}}, {{zh-m|*丮|kneeling person with hands stretched out}} appeared from bronze inscriptions onwards.

===Etymology 1===
Area etymon ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Compare {{cog|bo|ཕུང་པོ||heap}}, {{cog|bo|སྤུང||heap}}, {{cog|lep|ᰣᰦᰎᰪᰵ|tr=a-pŭŋ|gloss=a heap; a stock}}, {{cog|lus||tr=puŋᴴ}}, {{m|lus||tr=punᴸ|t=increase; assemble}}, {{cog|lus|vûng|tr=vuuŋᴴ}}, {{m|lus|vûn|tr=vuunᴸ|t=swollen}}, {{cog|lus|vûng|tr=vuuŋᴿ||heap; mound}}, {{cog|cdm|भुङ्‌हसा|tr=bhuŋh-|t=to be burst or peak of activity (flowering, field work etc.)}}. Compare also {{cog|km|ពោង||protuberances/bumps on an animal's head}}, {{cog|km|សំពោង||puffed up; swollen}}.

{{och-l|邦|country}} may be the same etymon ({{zh-ref|Wang, 1982, Schuessler, 2007}}).

